Since both sides are now expressed as a single natural logarithm, we can equate the arguments:

$$
\begin{aligned}
4 &= \dfrac{1}{x} \\
x &= \dfrac{1}{4}
\end{aligned}
$$

Because the question asks for the **exact value**, we leave it as a fraction or the exact decimal $0.25$.

Since we have $\ln(\text{something}) = \ln(\text{something else})$, the arguments must be equal. We can drop the logarithms and solve the resulting algebraic equation:

$$
\begin{aligned}
4 &= \dfrac{1}{x} \\
x &= \dfrac{1}{4}
\end{aligned}
$$

The exact value of $x$ is $\dfrac{1}{4}$ (or $0.25$).
